June·teenth
/ˌjo͞onˈtēnTH/
noun
a holiday celebrated on June 19 to commemorate the emancipation of enslaved people in the US. The holiday was first celebrated in Texas, where on that date in 1865, in the aftermath of the Civil War, enslaved people were declared free under the terms of the 1862 Emancipation Proclamation.

SORRY LONG SENTIMENTAL POST 🚨- Just wanted to  give ALL the gratitude to the universe for where I am on my journey to reaching my dreams right now . A year ago I decided to make the very very hard decision to leave my close and dear family at @complexions_ballet and set out on a personal artist journey to better find out who I am . I was very scared of the unknown and currently not exactly where I want to be financially . But honestly I’m more scared of what my life would have been like if I didn’t step outside the comfort of my 9-5 life !  A year later I am working with my first recording artist @serpentwithfeet and opening this years @thejoycetheater season with @rajafeatherkelly x @wu_tsang ! I know times are hard right now but I invite all of you to find something or someone to give gratitude to ( you can also celebrate this victory with me because when I win , we all win ) 🙏🏾 GIVE SOMEONE A HUG & thank you for your constant support .. thank you @beyonce & @travisscott for such an inspiring track
